MAM-Royal Crown Cola Co.
played the role Of Santa Claus
to the Morgan State College and
Florida A & M University foot
ball teams in the recent 3lst an
nual Orange Blossom Classic
and Festival.


The Columbus, Ga. soft drink
firm, and its Miami bottling at
filiate, in unprecedented activity
in a Negro athletic promotion,
introduced three significant
"hrsts" to spearhead the tie-in
participation among several Of
the nations leading commercial
firms in America s top sepia pro-
motional event.


A pioneer in the field Of ethnic
marketing. Royal Grown Cola
Co. scored "Classic" "firsts"
with the entertainment Of the two
teams at dinner, and with the put

ting into competition Of the first
annual Orange Blossom Classic
Championship Trophy. Nehi-RC
Bottling Co. Inc, Of Miami
scored its third First when 1t
spearheaded the spoons orship Of
the first annual Post-Parade
Teenage "Platter Party" which
attracted nearly thousand.
Royal Crown Cola presented gift
watches for the second consecu-
tive year to players and coaches
Of both teams.


Presentations were made by
Charles j. Smith, RC special
marketing director.


Edward B. Bell, assistant to
the director Of advertising and
sales promotion, Atlantic Refin-
Ing Company, Philadelphia, was
the principal speaker at the din
ner.

Fom the singing of spirituals
by the unframed voices of for
mer slaves to the footlights of
the Metropolitan Opera is, by
any measurement, a long way.
Yet in a century of Negro free
dom, this is precisely what has
happened, and the contribution
of the American Negro to the
creative and performing arts,
particularly in the field Of music,
has been an undisputable one.


The spiritual, Americas only
truly indigenous art form, pro-
vided perhaps the first medium
of musical expression. Through
the years it's appeal was great
ly enhanced by the arranging
genius of such authorities as
Harry T. Burleigh, Nathaniel
Dett, William Dawson and John
Work, most Of whom were also
responsible for developing music
in the Negro colleges.


Not far removed from the
spiritual form were the songs Of
early composer James A. Bland,
who was, in effect, the Negro
Stephen Foster. His most famous
work, "Carry Me Back to Old
Virginny," was adopted by the
Virginia legislature as the Off
cial State song in 1910.


Jazz, spawned by the spiritual,
developed into one of the ma
tons. authentic artistic exports,
and Negro instrumentalists were
among the foremost opponents of
this, universally popular art
form. With their trumpets, from
bones, coronets, piano dexterity
and sharp wit, such originators
as Sidney Bechet, Jelly Roll
Morton, King Oliver and Louis
Armstrong helped pave the way
forr-the acceptance of Negro
musicians. During the 1900's be-
fore the broad acceptance of
jazz, blues singers such as Ma
Rainey, and her student Bessie
Smith, Huddie Ledbetter, Mamie
Smith, and "Blind Lemon" JEFF
ferson appeared and went on to
become legend.


By far, the most indelible con-
tribution to the whole field of
the blues during the First
Century of Negro freedom was
made by William Christopher
Handy, internationally acclaimed
Father Of the Blues" Handy's

HiohIiqhtsl First Century Of Freedom

fame rests on the blues he COM
posed, and the earlier tunes he
collected and wrote down. His
St. Louis Blues" Memphis
Blues" and others became stand
ards for instrumentalists and vo-
calists even before his death, and
many renditions of these have
been recorded by RCA Victor.


AS the First Century of Negro
freedom moved forward, jazz, the
blues and other forms of popular
music continued to witness an
unbroken line of outstanding
Negro artists, many of whose
performances spanned a genera
ton or more. Ethel Waters, who
launched a many-faceted career
Of night club tours, recordings,
motion pictures, musical revues
and dramatic roles, Florence
Mills, featured in Sissle and
Blake's "Shuffle Along" revue,
the Mills Brothers, Buck and
Bubbles, Josephine Baker, Cab
Galloway, and Fats Waller were
among these. The combined tai
ents and genius Of Edward Ken
nedy Duke" Ellington have won
for him an indisputable place at
the head of this list.


New talents rose in phalan&
to take up the strains of music
that had it's beginnings in the.
rural South. By the close Of
1862, Negro performers had been
named for awards in fifteen OF
the categories cited by the Ma
tional Academy of Recording
Arts and Sciences.


One of the most meteoric rises
to stardom has been that of Har-
ry Belafonte, who turned from
the singing Of popular ballads to
create new interest in work
songs and traditional folk melo-
dies from the world over. The
volatile, handsome artist has
"glorifed" folk singing at night
clubs, in motion pictures, on
records, television, and on the
artistically hallowed stage Of
Carnegie Hall.


The First Century of Negro
freedom also saw that period OF
culture, often referred to as
the "Negro Renaissance" which
fiared in the middle twenties and
during which gifted figures
emerged in art, letters and

classical music. The brothers,
James Weldon johnson and j.
Rosamond johnson wrote music
plays and light operas; William
Grant Still, Clarence Cameron
White and Carl r. Diton COM:
posed; and Tenor Roland Hayes
sang his way into the hearts Of
thousands and demonstrated, at
72, in a Carnegie Hall Concert
that the years have not diminished
his talent.


If no other contribution had
been made by Negroes to the
field of classical music, that
racial group would still have
much to be proud Of in the soft
spoken, unassuming LADY from
Philadelphia" hailed as the
"voice of a century," Marian
Anderson, who rose from rela-
tive obscurity in a church choir
to apply her art to international
understanding, long ago became
a major symbol of Negro a.
chievement.


The ranks of Negroes in art
and culture swelled over the
years with new names and new
talents, and Dorothy Maynor,
Paul Robson, Todd Duncan
were among those who rose to
prominence. They were later
Joined by Muriel Smith, Anne
Brown, Muriel Rain, Camilla
Williams and Lawrence Winters
as well as by instrumentalists
who launched successful careers.


That the field of music has
been won by Negroes is further
evidenced by Mattiwilda Dobbs'
appearances with La Scala, and
Adele Addison and William War
fields inspiring performances
with the New York Philhar-
monte. Too, 1862 saw 23-year-old
Sanford Allen capture a violin
chair with the Philharmonic,
Mezzo-soprano Grace Bumbry re-
turned in triumph to her home
town Of st. Louis and opened
the city's symphony orchestra
series and pianist Phillipa
Schuyler, who has been astound-
ing audiences since she was
three, added yet another laurel
with a concert at New York's
Lincoln Center for the Perform
ing Arts.


And finally, before the First
Century's end, came the coveted
dream: the Met-the great
Metropolitan Opera Company.
Marian Anderson had sung Ul-
RIGA in Verdi's Gun Bal Masque,"
Robert McFerran and Gloria
Davey also made Met appear
ances, and more recently Leon
tyne Price won five starring roles
in a single Met season, and sang
the lead in an opening night per-
Torrance. In 1862, Miss Price,
an RCA Victor recording artist,
was named Musician Of the
Year" in a nationwide poll.


Thus, the Century's final cur
tain falls on what has been an
enviable harvest in the fine arts.

DR.. Charles H. Wesley. presi-
dent Of the Association for the
Study of Negro Life and History.
announces that Negro History
Week will be observed through
out the country Feb. o-l6. He
urges schools, churches and civ
ic groups to give attention to the
great strides made in civil lib
critics, but he cautions against
forgetting about Negro history.

First Institutional Baptist Church filled with congratulations
of praise faithful workers years Of service.
Mrs. Martha E. Billiard member Of the church since 1922
celebrated her S5 birthday JAM 21 She the the
Busy Bee Mission Circle.


Club chairman Mrs. billiard has devoted service
the church and the community


Special guests Mr.. and Mrs. Fred Bell Of Memphis Tenn.
Shown Mrs. Dard honoree
S5 birthday and her 4nd anniversary continuous church member
ship.


She is surrounded Mr.. and Mrs. Fred
G. Kendick Mr.. and Mrs. Solomon Garrett Mr. Mrs. James
Hunter Mrs. Maggie Brown, Mrs. Maud Johnson L. Ashy
Mrs. Mary L. Watson.


Mrs. S. Boyer served as chairman of the program
